question.title: Method not applicable for arguments regarding generics or type erasure in Java

node.contents: I ran into a problem regarding Java generics.

astNode.text: I ran into a problem regarding Java generics.

node.contents: I'm trying to make a listener (called SomeEventListener) which listens to SomeEvents to occur. Those events have a result which have a specific type; I want that result to be retrieved through the method getResult(), whose return type is T. When that event is fired, then the eventOccurred(SomeEvent<T>) method is called.

elements.contents: public class SomeEvent<T> { private T result; public SomeEvent(T result) { this.result = result; } public T getResult() { return this.result; } }

elements.contents: public interface SomeEventListener<T> { void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<T> event); }

units.rawText: public interface SomeEventListener<T> { void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<T> event); }

elements.contents: public class AnotherClass { ArrayList<SomeEventListener<?>> listeners = new ArrayList<SomeEventListener<?>>(); <T> void fireSomethingOccursEvent(SomeEvent<T> event) { for (SomeEventListener<?> listener : this.listeners) { listener.eventOccurred(event); // MARKED LINE } } }

node.contents: You have a SomeEventListener<?>, with a method void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<?> event) (substituting ? as T).

astNode.text: You have a SomeEventListener<?>, with a method void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<?> event) (substituting ? as T).

node.contents: You also have a SomeEvent<T> for some completely unrelated T.

astNode.text: You also have a SomeEvent<T> for some completely unrelated T.

node.contents: You can't convert this to a SomeEvent<?> - in fact, you can't convert anything to a SomeEvent<?> except for null. ? means "I have no idea what this type argument is."

astNode.text: You can't convert this to a SomeEvent<?> - in fact, you can't convert anything to a SomeEvent<?> except for null. ? means "I have no idea what this type argument is."

node.contents: As an example, if your code was allowed, this code would compile, but pass the wrong type:

astNode.text: As an example, if your code was allowed, this code would compile, but pass the wrong type:

elements.contents: AnotherClass ac = new AnotherClass(); ac.listeners.add(new SomeEventListener<Integer>() { void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<Integer> event) { System.out.println(event.intValue()); } }); SomeEvent<String> event = new SomeEvent<String>("Hello"); ac.fireSomethingOccursEvent(event);

units.rawText: AnotherClass ac = new AnotherClass(); aclistenersadd(new SomeEventListener<Integer>() { void eventOccurred(SomeEvent<Integer> event) { System.out.println(event.intValue()); } }); SomeEvent<String> event = new SomeEvent<String>("Hello"); acfireSomethingOccursEvent(event);

node.contents: Now fireSomethingOccursEvent would take the SomeEvent<String> and pass it to a SomeEventListener<Integer>. This obviously should not be allowed - so, it's not allowed.

astNode.text: Now fireSomethingOccursEvent would take the SomeEvent<String> and pass it to a SomeEventListener<Integer>. This obviously should not be allowed - so, it's not allowed.

node.contents: You can make whole AnotherClass generic and use wildcards:

astNode.text: You can make whole AnotherClass generic and use wildcards:

elements.contents: public class AnotherClass<T> { ArrayList<SomeEventListener<? super T>> listeners = new ArrayList<>(); //use diamond-type since java 1.7 void fireSomethingOccursEvent(SomeEvent<? extends T> event) { for (SomeEventListener<? super T> listener : this.listeners) { listener.eventOccurred(event); // should be fine } } }
